Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:3156:

    (&"labels", ClusterObserved::Labels(got)) => {
        let exp: Vec<usize> = case.expected.value...;
        if exp == *got {
            (true, ...)
        } else {
            (false, format!("labels mismatch: expected {exp:?}, got {got:?}"))
        }
    }

Issue: cluster LABELINGS are permutation-invariant. A k-means that produces [0, 1, 1, 2, 0] is IDENTICAL to one that produces [1, 2, 2, 0, 1] (just with cluster IDs relabeled). The current comparator treats these as different.

Current fixture (FSCI-P2C-009_cluster_core.json) only uses kind='labels' for DETERMINISTIC cluster functions:
    fcluster_single_2groups: fcluster with known threshold -> canonical label order
    fcluster_complete_3groups: same
    leaves_list_5pt: leaves_list returns a permutation in deterministic tree-walk order

These 3 cases pass because the Rust impl happens to label in the same order as scipy's. But the comparator is a latent bomb:
1. The moment a fuzz target (per frankenscipy-plyj / 83b8) or fixture extension adds a kmeans case with kind='labels', the comparator will flip pass -> fail on any rerun because kmeans initialization varies with rand seed (especially now that we bumped rand 0.10).
2. Similarly, dbscan label IDs are permutation-equivalent. Current fixture has dbscan scalar metrics (silhouette etc.) but not labels directly -- any future expansion will hit this.

Fix options:
1. Replace exact equality with partition equivalence:
       fn labelings_equivalent(lhs: &[usize], rhs: &[usize]) -> bool {
           // Compute cluster-id correspondence via Hungarian matching on a co-occurrence table
           // OR canonicalize both via 'first occurrence' renaming.
       }
2. Simpler approach that covers 90% of cases: canonicalize labels by 'first-occurrence order'. Relabel so cluster containing index 0 is cluster 0, etc.
3. For metrics where permutation matters (e.g. fcluster with explicit threshold), keep exact equality and tag the case with 'deterministic_labels': true so reviewers know the case relies on label-id stability.

Also: the kmeans centroid ordering has the same problem. compare_cluster_outcome's 'vq_result' branch at 3195 uses exact  and numeric tolerance on exp_dists -- codes are the cluster assignments and inherit the same permutation-invariance issue.

Related: plyj (stats fuzz), 83b8 (no seed corpus for fuzz), d09k (inline tolerance sites).

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:7659-7670 on 2026-04-22:

The docstring on run_differential_test:

    /// Run a differential conformance test against a fixture file.
    ///
    /// This is the generic entry point for the conformance harness. It:
    /// 1. Loads and parses the fixture file
    /// 2. Detects the fixture type (validate_tol, linalg_core, etc.)
    /// 3. Runs the Rust implementation against each case
    /// 4. Optionally runs the Python/SciPy oracle for comparison
    /// 5. Computes max_diff between Rust and expected outputs per case
    ///
    /// If the oracle is unavailable and 'oracle_config.required == false',
    /// the report marks oracle_status as 'Missing' and still validates
    /// against the fixture's embedded expected values.

Per my bead ivg5: 11 of 12 family runners NEVER invoke the Python oracle. Only run_differential_stats (since today) does. Every other runner skips step 4 entirely -- they probe scipy availability but never shell out to run a scipy_*_oracle.py script.

A reviewer reading this docstring would reasonably conclude that all 12 families perform differential comparison against scipy when scipy is available. That conclusion is wrong for 11 of them.

Fix:
1. Update the docstring to honestly describe current behavior:
       /// ... STATS runner invokes scipy_stats_oracle.py when available; all
       /// other family runners currently use fixture-embedded expected values
       /// for comparison. oracle_status field reports probe result but does
       /// not drive the pass/fail decision for non-stats families. Track
       /// frankenscipy-ivg5 for the broader wiring work.
2. Ideally: fix ivg5 (wire oracles to every runner) so the docstring becomes accurate instead of documenting a temporary state.

Related: ivg5 (the core bug), di9p (10 missing oracle scripts), cpgl (stats oracle landed today).

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:6950-6955:

    fn allclose_scalar(actual: f64, expected: f64, atol: f64, rtol: f64) -> bool {
        if actual.is_nan() && expected.is_nan() {
            return true;
        }
        (actual - expected).abs() <= atol + rtol * expected.abs()
    }

This function is the PRIMARY comparator used across EVERY differential_<family>_case_differential in crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs (integrate, stats, linalg, fft, special, sparse, signal, opt, cluster, spatial, ndimage). Verified call sites at lines 2039, 2581, 2624, 5387, 5414, and many more (grep -nE allclose_scalar crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs).

Bugs vs numpy.allclose (verified via numpy 2.4 reference):

Case                          | fsci returns | numpy returns | Correct
----------------------------- | ------------ | ------------- | -------
allclose_scalar(+inf, +inf)   | **false**    | True          | numpy
allclose_scalar(-inf, -inf)   | **false**    | True          | numpy
allclose_scalar(+inf, -inf)   | **true**     | False         | numpy (INVERTED)
allclose_scalar(-inf, +inf)   | **true**     | False         | numpy (INVERTED)
allclose_scalar(NaN, NaN)     | true         | False (def)   | divergent (equal_nan=True semantics)
allclose_scalar(NaN, 5.0)     | false        | False         | OK
allclose_scalar(+inf, 1e308)  | false        | False         | OK
allclose_scalar(5.0, 5.0)     | true         | True          | OK

Root cause: (INF - INF) in IEEE 754 is NaN, and NaN <= x is false for all x. Meanwhile (INF - -INF) = INF, which is <= INF + rtol * INF = INF — always true. So the comparator INVERTS the equality logic for opposite-sign infinities.

Impact:
- Rust implementation correctly returning +INF (e.g., gamma(-n) → +INF per standard convention; 1/0+ → +INF) when oracle also returns +INF: comparator reports MISMATCH and flags the case as a conformance failure.
- Rust returning +INF and oracle returning -INF (catastrophic sign flip): comparator reports MATCH, hiding the bug.
- The existing open beads d218 (complex_gammaln at poles) and jthj (wrightomega underflow) both involve infinity in outputs — their effects on conformance are undetermined because the comparator cannot correctly judge infinity.

Fix:
    fn allclose_scalar(actual: f64, expected: f64, atol: f64, rtol: f64) -> bool {
        if actual.is_nan() || expected.is_nan() {
            return actual.is_nan() && expected.is_nan();  // or false per numpy default
        }
        if actual.is_infinite() || expected.is_infinite() {
            // IEEE 754 equality: +inf == +inf and -inf == -inf; +inf != -inf.
            return actual == expected;
        }
        (actual - expected).abs() <= atol + rtol * expected.abs()
    }

Also: document whether NaN-matches-NaN is the intended convention (the current code says yes at line 6951-6953, which diverges from numpy's default equal_nan=False). If yes, say so in DISCREPANCIES.md (per ma1a bead) so users of the conformance dashboard understand the semantic.

Regression tests:
    assert!(allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, f64::INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(!allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, f64::NEG_INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(allclose_scalar(f64::NEG_INFINITY, f64::NEG_INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(!allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, 1e308, 1e-8, 1e-5));

Related: 37ip (no per-function tolerance contract), m9jp/pqka (other oracle correctness bugs that feed into this comparator), d218 (complex_gammaln returns inf at poles -- exposes both this bug and d218 simultaneously).

Review of crates/fsci-special/src/elliptic.rs:655-662:

    if z.im == 0.0 {
        if z.re > 0.0 {
            return exp1_scalar(z.re, mode).map(Complex64::from_real);
        }
        if z.re < 0.0 {
            return expi_scalar(-z.re, mode).map(|value| Complex64::new(-value, -PI));
        }
    }

The reflection E₁(-x ± 0i) = -Ei(x) ∓ iπ must differentiate the ±0 imaginary part. Current impl unconditionally returns `(-Ei(x), -π)` regardless of whether z.im is +0 or -0, because `z.im == 0.0` matches both in Rust.

Verification (scipy reference):
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-1,  0.0)) = (-1.895..., -π)   (our code correct)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-1, -0.0)) = (-1.895..., +π)   (our code returns -π, WRONG)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-2,  0.0)) = (-4.954..., -π)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-2, -0.0)) = (-4.954..., +π)   (our code returns -π)

Fix:
    let sign_pi = if z.im.is_sign_negative() { PI } else { -PI };
    return expi_scalar(-z.re, mode).map(|value| Complex64::new(-value, sign_pi));

Related: same ±0 pattern as 276r (complex_sqrt). Both affect conjugation symmetry:
  exp1(z.conj()) should equal exp1(z).conj(); current impl violates this for z on (-∞, 0).

Note: expi_complex_scalar at lines 767-769 delegates to expi_scalar for z.im == 0.0 (returning a purely real value); this IS CORRECT for expi — verified that scipy.special.expi(-1 ± 0i) = -0.219... with zero imag, so no ±0 distinction needed for expi.

Related: 276r (complex_sqrt -0), 0acr (fuzz EdgeF64 lacks ±0 imag sweep), tmti (new complex fuzz harness).

Review-mode audit of crates/fsci-special/src/convenience.rs:1987-2010:

    pub fn wrightomega_scalar(z: f64) -> f64 {
        let mut w = if z > 1.0 { z - z.ln() }
                    else if z > -2.0 { z.exp() / (1.0 + z.exp()) }
                    else { z.exp() };  // underflows to 0 for z <~ -745
        for _ in 0..50 {
            if w <= 0.0 { w = 1e-15; }           // <-- BUG
            let residual = w + w.ln() - z;
            if residual.abs() < 1e-15 { break; }
            w -= residual / (1.0 + 1.0 / w);
        }
        w
    }

Issue: for z in [-∞, -ln(MAX)] ≈ z ≤ -709, `z.exp()` underflows to 0. Newton loop then sees `w <= 0` and clamps to 1e-15, which becomes the 'answer' after iteration doesn't move much (because f'(w) = 1 + 1/w ≈ 1e15 for w = 1e-15, so Newton steps are tiny).

Verification vs scipy:
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-100)  = 3.72e-44   (CORRECT — Ω(z) ≈ exp(z) for z << 0)
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-20)   = 2.06e-09
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-800)  = 0.0         (underflow is fine here)
    our impl likely returns ~1e-15 for z in [-750, -25], off by up to 30+ orders of magnitude.

The clamp 'if w <= 0.0 { w = 1e-15; }' is doctrine-incompatible: fsci-special must fail-closed, not silently substitute wrong values.

Impact:
- Any downstream function calling wrightomega for deeply-negative arguments silently gets a catastrophically wrong result.
- wrightomega_complex_scalar (line 2022-2024) delegates to wrightomega_scalar for z.im == 0, inheriting the bug.

Fix:
1. Remove the clamp. When initial w is 0 (from underflow), Newton can't iterate (ln(0) = -inf) — detect this and return a Correct limiting value: for z << 0, Ω(z) ≈ z.exp() (including 0 if truly underflowed). Otherwise use a more careful scheme (e.g. log-domain Newton) that avoids representing w directly in f64.
2. Alternative: use scipy's Lawrence-Corless-Jeffrey iteration (arxiv:1501.02813) which handles the full range without underflow artifacts.
3. Add a convergence check at loop end: if |residual| is still > 1e-15 * max(1, |z|), return NaN or Err per mode doctrine.

Regression test suggestion:
    assert!((wrightomega_scalar(-100.0) / 3.72e-44 - 1.0).abs() < 1e-3);
    assert!((wrightomega_scalar(-20.0)  / 2.06e-09 - 1.0).abs() < 1e-6);
    assert_eq!(wrightomega_scalar(-800.0), 0.0);

Related: 276r (complex_sqrt -0 bug), tmti (new complex fuzz harnesses).

Review-mode audit of fuzz/fuzz_targets/:

The EdgeF64 enum in three fuzz harnesses defines a Nan variant (intended to exercise NaN handling) and a bounded() helper that collapses out-of-range values. But the collapse silently maps NaN -> finite:

  fuzz_targets/p2c006_special_bessel_derivatives.rs:49-60
      fn bounded(self) -> f64 {
          let raw = self.raw();
          if raw.is_finite() { raw.clamp(-16.0, 16.0) }
          else if raw.is_sign_positive() { 16.0 }
          else if raw.is_sign_negative() { -16.0 }
          else { 0.0 }
      }

Issue: f64::NAN.is_finite() is false, is_sign_positive() is true (NaN's sign bit default is +), is_sign_negative() is false. So NaN -> 16.0. The EdgeF64::Nan enum variant becomes indistinguishable from PosInf after bounded(), making NaN coverage claimed by the enum a FICTION.

Call sites affected:
  p2c006_special_bessel_derivatives.rs:237  let v = input.order.bounded();  -- Bessel order v can never be NaN in fuzz
  p2c006_special_elliptic_complex.rs:257-258 m = C(m_re.bounded(), m_im.bounded()); phi = C(phi_re.bounded(), phi_im.bounded())  -- all 4 elliptic args
  p2c006_special_incomplete_gamma_beta.rs:57, 66, 143-145  -- a_complex, b_complex, x_complex all via bounded()

Consequence: the fuzz targets advertise EdgeF64::Nan as part of the structure-aware input alphabet (per /testing-fuzzing archetype 5) but the alphabet is reduced from {Finite, Zero, NegZero, One, NegOne, Tiny, NegTiny, PosInf, NegInf, Nan} down to just finite edge values for every bounded() call site. This is roughly half the fuzz state space claimed.

Fix options (pick one per call site based on whether the function under test should accept NaN):
1. For kernels that should accept NaN and propagate it (most of special.*): use .raw() instead of .bounded().
2. For kernels that should reject NaN: keep .bounded() but separately add an explicit NaN test case at the top of the fuzz body:
       if matches!(input.order, EdgeF64::Nan) {
           // assert function rejects with domain error in Hardened, NaN in Strict
           let v_tensor = RealScalar(f64::NAN);
           assert!(matches!(jv(&v_tensor, &zt, mode), ...));
           return;
       }
3. Delete the EdgeF64::Nan variant entirely from harnesses where it's dead, and split into a separate nan-only fuzz target per skill archetype 1.

Related: 0acr (EdgeF64 range clamps mask overflow), tmti (complex fuzz gaps), il3p (mode coverage gaps).

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:7687-7716 on 2026-04-22:

Dispatch cascade uses substring matching on family name:
    if family.contains('validate_tol') { ... }
    else if family.contains('linalg') { ... }
    else if family.contains('array_api') { ... }
    else if family.contains('special') { ... }
    else if family.contains('fft') { ... }
    else if family.contains('optim') { ... }
    else if family.contains('casp') { ... }
    else if family.contains('cluster') { ... }
    else if family.contains('spatial') { ... }
    else if family.contains('signal') { ... }
    else if family.contains('stats') { ... }
    else if family.contains('integrate') { ... }
    else { Err('unknown fixture family: {family}') }

Problems (audit of actual fixture family strings: validate_tol, linalg_core, array_api, optimize_core, sparse_ops, fft_core, special_core, runtime_casp, cluster_core, spatial_core, signal_core, stats_core, integrate_core, integrate.validate_tol, constants_core):

1. CONFLICT: family='integrate.validate_tol' (used by FSCI-P2C-001_validate_tol.json) matches BOTH 'validate_tol' AND 'integrate'. Only works today because 'validate_tol' is checked first in the cascade. Reordering the cases or adding new families with overlapping substrings silently flips dispatch. A developer reading the dispatch code cannot easily see this fragility.

2. NO-MATCH: family='sparse_ops' and family='constants_core' match NO pattern. sparse_ops is handled elsewhere (PacketFamily::SparseOps registry at ~11235), not here, so it fails closed with 'unknown fixture family' if called through run_differential_test -- arguably OK. constants_core (FSCI-P2C-016) is entirely dead (utus bead).

3. FRAGILE: substring match means family='optimizer_v2_hybrid' (hypothetical) would match 'optim' pattern. Adding a prefix-related family silently routes to existing handler. No explicit test guards against this.

4. INCONSISTENT naming: some families use '_core' suffix (linalg_core, special_core, ...), some '_ops' (sparse_ops), some nothing (array_api, validate_tol). The suffix conveys no information to the dispatch -- it just has to not conflict with patterns.

Fix:
1. Introduce an explicit PacketFamilyName enum with ALL variants:
       pub enum PacketFamilyName { ValidateTol, LinalgCore, ArrayApi, ... }
2. Deserialize fixture.family via serde #[serde(rename = '...')] into the enum. Unknown family strings fail closed at parse time.
3. Replace family.contains() cascade with match on PacketFamilyName -- exhaustive, compiler-enforced.
4. Add a test that enumerates PacketFamilyName::ALL and verifies each dispatches to the expected runner function by calling and checking the returned family field in ConformanceReport.

Related: utus (P2C-016 constants_core dead), ivg5 (differential isn't differential), di9p (10 missing oracles).
